      <hedline>
        <hl1>Rebuild Downtown, And Remember</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Luther S Harris letter says Witold Rybczynski's March 25 Op-Ed article speaks for architects and planners who always hated World Trade Center towers; says rebuilding them, with better technology, is only real hope for quick solution for lower Manhattan (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Witold Rybczynski (''How Quickly a City Can Grow,'' Op-Ed, March 25) speaks for the architects and planners who have always hated the twin towers, while most everyone else loved them. Rebuilding the twin towers, with improved technology and infrastructure, is our only real hope for a solution that can be ''a simple one and soon,'' with a proven track record to boot.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Witold Rybczynski (''How Quickly a City Can Grow,'' Op-Ed, March 25) speaks for the architects and planners who have always hated the twin towers, while most everyone else loved them. Rebuilding the twin towers, with improved technology and infrastructure, is our only real hope for a solution that can be ''a simple one and soon,'' with a proven track record to boot.</p>
        <p>The World Trade Center succeeded magnificently as a business and transportation hub, as a tourist site and as an icon for the city. It was already a part of a combined commercial and residential neighborhood resurgence, and its future value as a memorial is unsurpassed.</p>
        <p>LUTHER S. HARRIS  New York, March 26, 2002</p>
      </block>
